SB.RS2.1.388997	GAACTGGA	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F1C2F2Q	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SB	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	RS2	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151517	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX SI.RS4.2.389039	CTCACTGT	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F7LCH7B	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SI	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	RS4	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX SC.C.1.389093	CAACTGCA	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F6RQY2S	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SC	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	C	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151539	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the SF.RS4.2.389021	CACACAGT	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F7DWRBT	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SF	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	RS4	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX SF.WO.4.389015	ATGCGGTT	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F7DWRBT	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SF	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	WO	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151583	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the SE.BL.2.389059	GGCGAATA	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F6RQY2S	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SE	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	BaseLine	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151558	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX SA.BL.1.389120	AACGATCC	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F1C2F2Q	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SA	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	BaseLine	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151493	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the SD.BL.2.389031	CCGGAATT	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F6RQY2S	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SD	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	BaseLine	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151543	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the SI.RS2.3.389110	CGCCAATA	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F7LCH7B	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SI	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	RS2	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151632	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the SI.WO.4.388990	GAACTGGA	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F7LCH7B	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SI	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	WO	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX SH.WO.5.389082	AGGAACCA	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F7LCH7B	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SH	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	WO	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151621	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the SF.WO.1.388984	ACGAAGCA	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F7DWRBT	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SF	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	WO	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151577	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX SH.RS4.2.389087	TAGCATGC	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F7DWRBT	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SH	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	RS4	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX SE.C.3.389019	TGCAACCA	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F6RQY2S	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SE	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	C	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX SE.WO.2.389138	TACCAACG	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F6RQY2S	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SE	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	WO	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151563	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the SD.C.2.388988	CGATAAGG	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F6RQY2S	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SD	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	C	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151545	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the SJ.C.2.389131	GTCAGACT	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F7LCH7B	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SJ	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	C	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151647	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the SA.WO.3.389066	ATCCGCAA	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F1C2F2Q	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SA	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	WO	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151503	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the SH.RS2.3.389128	AGCTGATC	ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	V13	y	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the Fecal Microbiota in Human Subjects	F7LCH7B	408170	0	9606	human gut metagenome	-96.68	1180.6	2009	2009	0.0	ENVO:human-associated habitat	Titanium	GAZ:United States of America	SH	None	University of Nebraska	.25,g	RS2	495	The aim of the present study was to gain a community wide perspective of the effects of RS types 2 (RS2) and 4 (RS4) on the fecal microbiota in human individuals	human gut metagenome	human	pyrosequencing	ENVO:feces	16S rRNA	ENVO:human-associated habitat	TCAG	None	University of Nebraska	FWD:CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG;REV:ATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG	Fecal homogenates were thawed and transferred to sterile bead beating tubes containing 300 mg of zirconium beads. Cells were recovered by centrifugation (8,000_g for 5 min at room temperature) and suspended in ice-cold PBS to wash the cells. This step was repeated twice before cell pellets were suspended in 100 ?l of lysis buffer (200 mM NaCl, 100 mM Tris, 20 mM EDTA, 20 mg/ml Lysozyme, pH 8.0) containing 20 mg/ml of Lysozyme and incubated at 37?C for half an hour. Buffer ASL (1.6 ml) from QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit was added to each sample, after which the samples were homogenized in a MiniBeadbeater-8 for 2 min at maximum speed. 1.2 ml of supernatant was used to purify DNA with the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit following the manufacturer's instructions. The V1-V3 region of the 16S rRNA gene was amplified by PCR from fecal DNA. The 16S primers were modified to work with the Roche-454 Titanium adapter sequences and contain the A or B Titanium sequencing adapter (shown in italics), followed immediately by a unique 8-base barcode sequence (BBBBBBBB) and finally the 5_ end of primer. A mixture (4:1) of the primers B-8FM (5_- CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG?3_) and B-8FMBifido (5_-CCTATCCCCTGTGTGCCTTGGCAGTCTCAGAGGGTTCGATTCTGGCTCAG?3_) were used as the forward primer during PCR. As the reverse primer, the primer A-518R (5_- CCATCTCATCCCTGCGTGTCTCCGACTCAGBBBBBBBBATTACCGCGGCTGCTGG ?3_) was used. Individual samples were amplified with primers containing unique barcodes, which allowed the mixing of PCR products from multiple samples in a single run, followed by bioinformatic assignation of the sequences to their respective samples via the barcode. Primer 8FMBifido was used in combination with primer 8FM to detect bifidobacteria, as species within this genus do not match the latter primer. The PCR mixture contained 1 ?l of forward primer mix, 1 ?l of reverse primer, 0.25 ?l of Ex-Taq polymerase, 1.5 ?l of the sample, 6.25 ?l of Ex-Taq buffer, 5 ?l of deoxynucleotides and 37 ?l of sterile dH2O were used for the reaction. The PCR program consisted of an initial denaturing step for 5 min at 95?C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95?C for 45 sec, annealing at 57?C for 45 sec and extension at 72?C for 2 min, with a final step at 72?C for 10 min. The PCR products were quantified based on their staining intensity using the image acquisition software Genesnap. PCR products were combined in equal amounts and gel purified using the QIAquick Gel Extraction Kit. Pyrosequencing was performed by the Core for Applied Genomics and Ecology (CAGE, University of Nebraska) from the A end with the 454/Roche A sequencing primer kit using a Roche Genome Sequencer GS-FLX following manufacturer's protocol for the Roche 454 GS FLX Titanium.	40.81	PMID: 21151620	0	University of Nebraska	Resistant Starches Types 2 and 4 Have Differential Effects on the Composition of the
